The main goal of this work has been a mathematical investigation of optimal controls for the SIR model with a controlled rate of contact, as presented in the previous sections. We now present a brief illustration of the results in practical terms through application to the current COVID-19 pandemic. This application is imprecise, for several reasons: the SIR model is one of the simplest epidemiological models, and assumes homogeneous mixing among a population; the current state of susceptible and infected persons is not accurately known; and the parameters of the disease itself (i.e. \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
